Amazon EventBridge: API Destinations Demystified-Part I

Sheen Brisals

·

8 min read
·
Aug 11, 2021

Amazon EventBridge is becoming one of the widely used serverless services of AWS. Along with the expanding set of features, its industry adoption is also growing fast.

Amazon EventBridge is a serverless event bus that makes it easier to connect applications with data from a variety of sources.

One of the great benefits of developing on AWS is the possibility of using native service integrations that eliminate the need for lambda functions acting as mediators and data-shifters. Terms such as code-less and functionless often refer to these integration patterns.

API Destinations is one such cool feature that promotes native service integration to reach external API targets.

This is a two-part article on API destinations. In this first part, we will look at the features of API destinations, its benefits, integration options, and a use case on how it helps to communicate between microservices.

In a subsequent article, we will see how to store API credentials in Secrets Manager and make it work with EventBridge cost-efficiently.

What Are API Destinations?

API destinations are HTTP endpoints that can be configured as targets for event routing rules. They help integrate with applications using RESTful API calls.

A Connection is the core of an API destination. It defines the authorization method and the credentials to connect to an endpoint.

As shown above, a connection supports the following authorization methods.

  • Basic auth
  • API Key auth
  • OAuth

Event Routing Rule With API Destinations

The following diagram captures the main elements of a rule with API destinations as the target.

Common Use Cases

The purpose of API destinations is, of course, to deliver events to targets. However, the types of targets could differ based on the use case.

Take, for instance, the AWS SaaS Partner integrations. It allows us to send metrics and operational data directly to a monitoring application without having to write any lambda function.

The second most common use case is for sending events to webhooks. Let us say, your Payment Service accepts a batch of payment numbers to initiate the settlement process. There could be thousands of payments in every batch. As it is an asynchronous processing flow, API destinations can be used to send task progress notifications to the client’s webhook.

In addition, API destinations can play its part in triggering execution flows between microservices as well. The example discussed in this article is of this type.

In future, it may support more use cases as per a feature request made to have the ability to receive API responses as well.

Important Characteristics

A few points on API destinations that may influence your architectural decisions and design choices are,

  • EventBridge will timeout a target invocation after five seconds and retry as per the retry setting.
  • Due to its retry mechanism, targets could receive duplicate requests. Make sure the services are idempotent to handle this.
  • While it supports most of the HTTP methods, POST and PUT are the most common ones.
  • As you can assume, the ideal use cases for API destinations are endpoints that act as asynchronous invocation targets.
  • EventBridge uses AWS Secrets Manager to store the API credentials. We will explore how EventBridge uses the service-linked role with Secrets Manager for this in the next part.

API Destinations Use Case

For our discussion, we will use the example depicted above.

Customers who shop at a store can opt to join a loyalty program. The Loyalty Service quickly enrolls a shopper in the program. Customers who have enrolled can start collecting reward points for their purchases.

However, complete customer registration is handled by the Customer Accounts Service. After successful enrollment, the Loyalty Service sends the details to the Customer Accounts Service to trigger the registration process.

In the above case, though, the customer registration API is secured with OAuth. The team favors an API-based invocation for the following reasons:

  • It streamlines the access for internal, as well as external clients using the same functionality
  • It controls the authorization of different clients with API scopes
  • It allows the setting of an API usage quota per client
  • It promotes better monitoring at a granular level

In this blog series, we will look at creating and configuring API destinations with an OAuth connection.

For details on API Key and Basic authorization, please refer to Using API Destinations with Amazon EventBridge by James Beswick, Principal Developer Advocate for Serverless at Amazon Web Services.

Architecture

The high-level flow is so simple! After successful enrollment, the Loyalty Service sends an event to the custom bus. An EventBridge rule to filter in the event transforms and sends it to the Customer Accounts endpoint using API destinations.

Before we look at the API destination, let us go through the preliminary parts of the routing rule setup. It includes the source event, event filter pattern, target payload structure, and event transformation.

Source Event

Given below is a loyalty enrollment custom event. For simplicity, it shows just the detail part of an EventBridge event.

{
  "detail": {
    "metadata": {
      "domain": "LEGO-LOYALTY",
      "service": "service-loyalty",
      "category": "loyalty-enroll",
      "status": "success"
    },
    "data": {
      "loyalty_number": "loyal-007",
      "first_name": "First",
      "last_name": "Last",
      "email": "first@email.com",
      "country": "GB"
    }
  }
}

Event Filter Pattern

It is a simple pattern that filters all successful loyalty enrollments that originate from a particular business domain.

{
  "detail": {
    "metadata": {
      "domain": [
        "LEGO-LOYALTY"
      ],
      "category": [
        "loyalty-enroll"
      ],
      "status": [
        "success"
      ]
    }
  }
}

Destination API Payload

As shown below, the payload structure of the Customer Accounts API is different from the enrollment event.

{
  "account_id": "loyal-007",
  "name": "First",
  "surname": "Last",
  "email_address": "first@email.com",
  "country_code": "GB",
  "requester": "service-loyalty"
}

EventBridge has support for handling such situations. There are three event data transformation options available as part of a routing rule configuration.

For further details on the transformation options, please refer to my article, The power of Amazon EventBridge is in its details.

Event Data Transformation

Here, we use the Input Transformer option to transform the source event to match the target.

Input Transformer has two parts, Input path and Input template, as shown below.

First, we identify the required attributes from the source event. Using JSONPath, we then copy those values and store them in variables, as below.

{
  "account_id": "$.detail.data.loyalty_number",
  "country_code": "$.detail.data.country",
  "email_address": "$.detail.data.email",
  "name": "$.detail.data.first_name",
  "surname": "$.detail.data.last_name",
  "requester": "$.detail.metadata.service"
}

Once we have identified the required values, we construct the target event structure using those variables.

{
  "account_id": "<account_id>",
  "name": "<name>",
  "surname": "<surname>",
  "email_address": "<email_address>",
  "country_code": "<country_code>",
  "requester": "<requester>"
}

Target Selection

The final part after completing the input configuration is choosing the event target. In our case, it is the API destination, as shown below.

With the initial part of the routing rule completed, the remainder of this article shows you how to configure the API destination via the EventBridge console.

API Destination Setup

Before we look at the destination, let’s configure an OAuth connection.

Connection

The first part of creating an OAuth connection is supplying the authorization endpoint. EventBridge will invoke this endpoint to fetch access tokens before invoking the destination endpoint.

Along with the authorization endpoint, we need to provide the client credentials - Client ID and Client Secret.

When we fill in the credentials on the console, EventBridge will create a secret in Secrets Manager and store the values there.

As in the picture above, we can configure Invocation and OAuth HTTP parameters. There are six different types available to choose from the list. Depending on the nature of a parameter, its value can be fetched from a secret, the event body using JSONPath or supplied as a static value.

When you create a connection, EventBridge will validate the endpoint and authorize based on the supplied details. The console reflects the status, as below.

Destination

With a successful and authorized connection in place, it’s time to create the API destination for the customer registration.

As we can see, the following destination uses the CustomerAccounts connection that we created above.

One thing to highlight from a resiliency point of view is that even though the invocation rate limit value is optional, I would recommend using it to protect your target service.

Once successfully created, it will become visible in the console along with its status.

Once the destination is in place, we can now complete the event routing rule configuration by pointing to the above API destination.

If required, header and query parameters can be created and associated with the target resource.

To Continue

I hope this article has given you a quick introduction to API destinations and how to configure and use them.

In a subsequent article, we will look at the best practices to handle the API credentials and a way to link EventBridge and Secrets Manager to keep your costs down and to keep your secrets secret!
